"Watterson I.G., Whetton P.H.","Distributions of decadal means of temperature and precipitation change under global warming",2011,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","116","7", D07101,"","",,,10.1029/2010JD014502,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79953720869&partnerID=40&md5=b5115209e851746a4d69264bb8103195","Centre for Australian Weather and Climate Research, PB1, Aspendale, VIC 3195, Australia","Watterson, I.G., Centre for Australian Weather and Climate Research, PB1, Aspendale, VIC 3195, Australia; Whetton, P.H., Centre for Australian Weather and Climate Research, PB1, Aspendale, VIC 3195, Australia","There remains uncertainty in the projected climate change over the 21st century, in part because of the range of responses forced by rising greenhouse gas concentrations among global climate models. This paper applies a method of estimating distributions and ""probability density functions"" (PDFs) for forced change, based on the pattern scaling technique and previously used for Australia, to generate changes in temperature and precipitation at locations over the globe, from simulations of 23 CMIP3 models. Changes for 2030 and 2100, under the A1B scenario for concentrations, for both seasonal and annual cases are presented. The PDFs for temperature have a standard deviation that averages 31% of the mean change, and they tend to be positively skewed. The standard deviation for precipitation averages 15% of the base climate mean, leading to five and 95 percentile estimates that are of opposite sign for most of the globe. A further source of uncertainty of change for a particular period of time, such as a decadal average, is the unforced or internal variability of climate. A joint probability distribution approach is used to produce PDFs for decadal means by adding in an estimate of internal variability. In the decade centered on 2030, this broadens the PDFs substantially. The results are related to time series of observations and projections over 1900-2100 for the agricultural regions of Iowa and the Murray-Darling Basin. For most land areas, warming becomes clearly discernable, allowing for both uncertainties, in the next few decades. Data files of the key results are provided. Copyright 2011 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Climate models; Computer simulation; Estimation; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Probability density function; Time series; Australia; Data files; Gas concentration; Global climate model; Internal variability; Land areas; Murray-Darling Basin; Precipitation change; Standard deviation; Probability distributions; climate change; climate modeling; decadal variation; greenhouse gas; precipitation intensity; probability; temperature gradient; time series; twenty first century; Australia; Iowa; Murray-Darling Basin; United States",,,,,,"Andersson, E., Assimilation and modeling of the atmospheric hydrological cycle in the ECMWF forecasting system (2005) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 86, pp. 387-402. , doi:10.1175/BAMS-86-3-387; Annan, J.D., Hargreaves, J.C., Reliability of the CMIP3 ensemble (2010) Geophys. Res. Lett., 37, pp. L02703. , doi:10.1029/2009GL041994; Christensen, J.H., Regional climate projections (2007) Climate Change 2007. the Physical Science Basis, pp. 847-940. , edited by S. Solomon et al. , Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge, U. K; (2007) Climate Change in Australia, Tech. Rep. 2007, , http://www.climatechangeinaustralia.gov.au/technical_report.php, CSIRO, Melbourne, Victoria, Australia; Dessai, S., Lu, X., Hulme, M., Limited sensitivity analysis of regional climate change probabilities for the 21st century (2005) J. Geophys. Res., 110, pp. D19108. , doi:10.1029/2005JD005919; Gleckler, P.J., Taylor, K.E., Doutriaux, C., Performance metrics for climate models (2008) J. Geophys. Res., 113, pp. D06104. , doi:10.1029/2007JD008972; Hawkins, E., Sutton, R., The potential to narrow uncertainty in regional climate predictions (2009) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 90, pp. 1095-1107